hands_on_practices.problem:
A simplified model for the oscillatory activity of a pair of coupled neurons is described by the dimensionless state variables $x(t)$ and $y(t)$, which obey the following system of differential equations:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\dot{x} = x - y - x^{3} \\
\dot{y} = x + y - y^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$
The system is known to possess a stable limit cycle. Its existence can be demonstrated by defining an annular trapping region in the phase plane. A key part of this demonstration involves identifying two critical radii. The first is a radius $R_{outward}$, such that for any circle centered at the origin with a radius $r$ in the range $0  r  R_{outward}$, the flow field $(\dot{x}, \dot{y})$ points strictly away from the origin at every point on that circle. The second is a radius $R_{inward}$, such that for any circle with a radius $r  R_{inward}$, the flow field points strictly towards the origin at every point on that circle.

Determine the maximum possible value for $R_{outward}$ and the minimum possible value for $R_{inward}$ for which these strict conditions hold for all points on the respective circles.

Provide your answer as the two values $R_{outward}$ and $R_{inward}$, in that specific order.
